data=wbdc
# # this shows that we need to tell R which columns contain factors 
#data$hd <- ifelse((test= (data$diagnosis) == "M"), yes="Malignant", no="Benign") 
data$hd <- ifelse(test = data$diagnosis == "M", yes = "Malignant", no = "Benign")

data$hd <- as.factor(data$hd)
logistic_simple <- glm(hd ~ diagnosis, data=data, family="binomial")
## Warning: glm.fit: algorithm did not converge
summary(logistic_simple)

#The output above shows the logistic regression results with hd as the dependent variable and diagnosis as the independent variable. Since there are only two levels in the diagnosis variable (M and B), the model estimates only one coefficient for the variable (i.e., diagnosisM). The estimate for diagnosisM is 53.13, which represents the log(odds ratio) comparing the odds of hd being true for malignant tumors (diagnosisM) relative to the odds of hd being true for benign tumors (the reference category).

#Based on the small p-value for the diagnosisM coefficient, we can infer that there is strong evidence that the log(odds) of hd being true for malignant tumors is significantly different from the log(odds) of hd being true for benign tumors. Specifically, the odds of hd being true for malignant tumors are significantly higher than the odds of hd being true for benign tumors.

#The null deviance represents the deviance when the response variable is modeled only by the intercept, while the residual deviance represents the deviance of the model after accounting for the effect of the predictor variable(s). In this case, the residual deviance is very small compared to the null deviance, indicating that the predictor variable (diagnosis) explains a significant amount of the variation in the response variable (hd). The AIC value of 4 is very low, indicating that the model has a good fit. Finally, the number of Fisher Scoring iterations is the number of iterations required for the algorithm to converge and find the maximum likelihood estimate of the coefficients. The fact that it took 25 iterations suggests that the model is not particularly simple, but it does not necessarily mean that it is bad.

# Convert the response variable to a factor
wbdc$diagnosis <- as.factor(wbdc$diagnosis)

# Check the levels of the response variable
levels(wbdc$diagnosis)
## [1] "B" "M"
# Set the correct level order
wbdc$diagnosis <- relevel(wbdc$diagnosis, ref = "B")

lr_model <- glm(diagnosis ~ radius_mean + texture_mean + perimeter_mean + area_mean + smoothness_mean + compactness_mean + concavity_mean + concave_pts_mean + symmetry_mean + fractal_dim_mean, 
             data = wbdc, family = binomial(link = "logit"))
## Warning: glm.fit: fitted probabilities numerically 0 or 1 occurred
summary(lr_model)

#The Deviance Residuals are used to evaluate the goodness of fit of the logistic regression model. The values range from -inf to inf, but in this case, the minimum value is -1.95590 and the maximum value is 2.91690. The median is negative and close to zero, indicating that the model is a good fit for the data. However, the maximum value is relatively high, suggesting that there may be some outliers or influential observations in the dataset. 

#The coefficients table provides information on the estimated regression coefficients and their statistical significance. 
#The Intercept has a negative value, and none of the coefficients appear to be statistically significant except for texture_mean, area_mean, smoothness_mean, and concave_pts_mean, which have p-values less than 0.05. 
#The coefficients for radius_mean, perimeter_mean, compactness_mean, concavity_mean, symmetry_mean, and fractal_dim_mean do not appear to be significant predictors of the response variable. The standard error measures the variability of the coefficient estimates, and the z-value measures the significance of the corresponding coefficient.
#The Signif. codes indicate the level of significance of the coefficients with p-values less than 0.001 marked as ***, p-values between 0.001 and 0.01 marked as **, p-values between 0.01 and 0.05 marked as *, p-values between 0.05 and 0.1 marked as ., and p-values greater than 0.1 marked as blank.

#The Deviance Residuals show the differences between the observed values and the fitted values, with the majority of the residuals falling within a reasonable range, except for some outliers.

#The Coefficients section shows the estimated coefficients for each predictor variable in the model. The p-values under Pr(>|z|) provide evidence for determining the significance of each predictor variable in the model.

#The Null deviance and Residual deviance indicate the goodness of fit of the model. The difference between the Null deviance and Residual deviance shows the reduction in deviance due to the model fit. In this case, the model appears to have performed well, as there is a significant reduction in deviance. The AIC value provides a measure of the relative quality of the model, with lower values indicating better fit.

#Overall, based on the output provided, it appears that a significant relationship exists between the predictor variables and the outcome variable, with some predictors being more significant than others. However, further information is needed to determine the specific context and interpretation of this analysis.

#The second column diagnosis contains the actual diagnoses of the tumors (either "M" for malignant or "B" for benign) for each observation in the wbdc data set.

#By creating this data frame, we can use it to make plots and calculate performance metrics such as accuracy, sensitivity, and specificity of the logistic regression model.


## We can plot the data...
ggplot(data=predicted.data, aes(x=diagnosis, y=as.numeric(probability.of.hd))) +
  geom_point(aes(color=diagnosis), size=5) +
  xlab("Diagnosis") + ylab("Predicted probability of tumor being malignant")

It is a scatter plot with the predicted probability on the y-axis and the diagnosis on the x-axis. Each point on the plot represents a tumor in the dataset. The color of the point represents the actual diagnosis of the tumor (malignant or benign).

#From the plot, we can see that the predicted probability of malignancy is generally higher for tumors that are actually malignant (represented by the blue points) compared to those that are benign (represented by the red points). #output of 0 indicates that the proposed logistic regression model does not provide a better fit to the data than the null model. This means that the inclusion of the predictor variable(s) did not improve the model fit significantly, and the null model (model with only intercept) is preferred.
predicted.data <- data.frame(probability.of.hd=logistic$fitted.values,hd=data$hd)
#a new data frame predicted.data is created which consists of two columns: probability.of.hd and hd.
#probability.of.hd column contains the predicted probabilities of the logistic regression model logistic on the input data data.
#hd column contains the actual response values of the input data data.

predicted.data <- predicted.data[order(predicted.data$probability.of.hd, decreasing=FALSE),]
#the predicted.data data frame is rearranged in ascending order based on the values in the probability.of.hd column. This is done using the order() function, with the argument decreasing=FALSE.

#The purpose of this rearrangement is to prepare the data frame for the calculation of the cumulative gains and lift charts, which are often used in binary classification problems to evaluate the performance of a model.

predicted.data$rank <- 1:nrow(predicted.data)
#The rank variable is assigned the value of the row number for each row in the data frame. The rank variable can be used to examine the distribution of the predicted probabilities by rank. 
## Lastly, we can plot the predicted probabilities for each sample having
## heart disease and color by whether or not they actually had heart disease
ggplot(data=predicted.data, aes(x=rank, y=probability.of.hd)) +
geom_point(aes(color=hd), alpha=1, shape=4, stroke=2) +
xlab("Index") +
ylab("Predicted probability of tumor being malignant")

#The plot is showing the predicted probability of the tumor being malignant for each observation in the dataset, ordered by their rank. The x-axis represents the index or rank of the observation, and the y-axis represents the predicted probability of the tumor being malignant. The color of the points represents the actual nature of the tumor, with blue indicating malignant and red indicating benign

#From the plot, we can see that the majority of the points with high predicted probabilities are blue, indicating that they are malignant.  Overall, the plot suggests that the logistic regression model is able to accurately predict the nature of the tumors in the dataset.

The plot generated by roc(data$hd,logistic$fitted.values,plot=TRUE) shows the ROC curve with true positive rate (sensitivity) on the y-axis and false positive rate (1-specificity) on the x-axis. The curve is plotted by varying the threshold for classifying a sample as positive (Malign) and negative (Benign). A curve that lies closer to the top-left corner of the plot indicates a better classifier. Since the AUC is 1, it indicates that the model is a perfect classifier that can completely distinguish between the two classes with no misclassifications.
